{"event":"pre-tool-use","timestamp":"2026-06-05T15:25:14.682Z","tool_name":"Write","tool_input":{"file_path":"/home/fragnot/Project/full-stack-engineer/role-config.json","content":"{\n  \"roleSlug\": \"full-stack-engineer\",\n  \"roleTitle\": \"Full Stack Engineer\",\n  \"stack\": \"c#, .NET, vue.js\",\n  \"domain\": \"\",\n  \"featureDescription\": \"# Stratus Build Challenge — Fabrication Tracker\\n\\n**Role:** Full Stack Engineer (AI-Driven)\\n**Format:** Proctored live session\\n**Timebox:** 60 minutes of focused work.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What we are actually assessing\\n\\nThis is not a \\\"can you write a CRUD app\\\" test. You will use AI tooling — that is the job, and we expect it. Because of that, working code is table stakes and counts for relatively little on its own.\\n\\nWhat we are reading for is everything AI *can't* one-shot for you:\\n\\n- Where you rejected or reworked AI output, and why.\\n- How you validated what an agent produced before trusting it.\\n- How fast you ramped on a codebase you didn't write.\\n- How you scoped an ambiguous requirement instead of guessing.\\n- How you found a bug in code an agent wrote.\\n\\nUse Claude Code, Cursor, Codex, Copilot, whatever your real dev loop is. Show us how you actually work.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Domain primer (no MEP experience needed)\\n\\nStratus builds software for **MEP contractors** — the companies that fabricate and install the piping, ductwork, and electrical systems inside buildings. You do **not** need to know anything about that industry to do this challenge. Here is everything you need:\\n\\nA **spool** is a prefabricated bundle of pipe and fittings built in a shop and shipped to a job site to be installed. Think of it as a kit with a parts list. Every spool moves through a sequence of stations:\\n\\n```\\nDetailing  →  Cut  →  Weld  →  QC  →  Shipped  →  Installed\\n```\\n\\nEach spool belongs to a **package** (a group of spools for one area of a job), has a **bill of materials** (its parts list), and a **due date**. A shop wants to know: what's in progress at each station, what's running late, and how fast work is actually flowing. That's the whole domain.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What we provide\\n\\nA starter repo (`stratus-fab-tracker`) containing:\\n\\n- A small **.NET API** + **Vue/TypeScript** front end + in-memory dataset seeded from JSON (~200 spools across several packages, with status-change history). No database installation is required.\\n- Existing dashboard and throughput endpoints and views.\\n- A `README` with run instructions.\\n- Optional project hook configs for Claude Code, Cursor, and Codex that may append structured events to `interview.log`.\\n\\n**Heads up:** parts of this starter were generated with AI and lightly reviewed. It runs, but it has rough edges — exactly the kind you'd inherit on a real team. Treat it as a codebase you've just been handed, not as a reference you should trust.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## The build\\n\\n### Advance a spool and reflect it on the dashboard\\n\\n- An endpoint to record a status transition for a spool.\\n- The dashboard should show **WIP per station** and **spools past due**.\\n- A spool can only move forward through the sequence. Decide what happens on an invalid transition and enforce it.\\n\\n### Throughput metric (deliberately under-specified)\\n\\nAdd a **throughput** view: roughly, how many spools are completing per day, and whether that's keeping up with what's due. Make reasonable decisions, state your assumptions, and move on.\\n\\n### Fix what's wrong\\n\\nThe starter has at least one real bug in its existing logic — the kind that passes a casual glance and a happy-path demo but is wrong. Find it, explain it, fix it, and prove the fix.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Deliverables\\n\\n1. **The code**, with clear run instructions.\\n2. **`PROCESS.md`** — what AI tools you used, where AI output was wrong, how you validated your code, your throughput assumptions, and what you'd do next.\\n3. **Tests** covering the transition logic and throughput metric.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Ground rules\\n\\n- **AI is encouraged.** Use your real workflow.\\n- **Timebox is real.** Ship a coherent slice; cut scope openly rather than running over.\\n- **Don't gold-plate.** This is not a production system. We're not grading polish.\",\n  \"timeBoxMinutes\": 60,\n  \"projectMode\": \"A\",\n  \"analysisMode\": \"ai-assisted\",\n  \"rubricMode\": \"default\",\n  \"outputDir\": \"./interviews/full-stack-engineer\",\n  \"jdPath\": \"/home/fragnot/Project/teamhero.cli/.claude/worktrees/nifty-mendeleev-620492/jd.md\",\n  \"jdInfluencesProject\": true\n}\n"}}
